04426nam a22007095i 9781503603950DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20202017cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2017012270  a97815036039507 a10.1515/97815036039502doi  a(DE-B1597)563658  a(OCoLC)1178769368  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aBP63.I42bT363 2018 4aBP63.I42bT363 2018eb 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a297.39095456223  aLB 463852rvk1 aTaneja, Anand Vivek, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJinnealogy :bTime, Islam, and Ecological Thought in the Medieval Ruins of Delhi /cAnand Vivek Taneja. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSouth Asia in Motion00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Walking Away from the Theater of History -- t1. Jinnealogy: Archival Amnesia and Islamic Theology in Post-Partition Delhi -- t2. Saintly Visions: The Ethics of Elsewhen -- t3. Strange(r)ness -- t4. Desiring Women -- t5. Translation -- t6. Stones, Snakes, and Saints: Remembering the Vanished Sacred Geographies of Delhi -- t7. The Shifting Enchantments of Ruins and Laws in Delhi -- tConclusion: Remnants of Despair, Traces of Hope -- tPostscript -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the ruins of a medieval palace in Delhi, a unique phenomenon occurs: Indians of all castes and creeds meet to socialize and ask the spirits for help. The spirits they entreat are Islamic jinns, and they write out requests as if petitioning the state. At a time when a Hindu right wing government in India is committed to normalizing a view of the past that paints Muslims as oppressors, Anand Vivek Taneja's Jinnealogy provides a fresh vision of religion, identity, and sacrality that runs counter to state-sanctioned history. The ruin, Firoz Shah Kotla, is an unusually democratic religious space, characterized by freewheeling theological conversations, DIY rituals, and the sanctification of animals. Taneja observes the visitors, who come mainly from the Muslim and Dalit neighborhoods of Delhi, and uses their conversations and letters to the jinns as an archive of voices so often silenced. He finds that their veneration of the jinns recalls pre-modern religious traditions in which spiritual experience was inextricably tied to ecological surroundings. In this enchanted space, Taneja encounters a form of popular Islam that is not a relic of bygone days, but a vibrant form of resistance to state repression and post-colonial visions of India.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aIslamxRelationsxHinduism. 0aIslamzIndiazDelhi. 0aIslamic antiquitieszIndiazDelhi. 0aJinnzIndiazDelhi. 0aMuslim saintszIndiazDelhi. 4a(anthropology of) ethics. 4aIslam. 4aSouth Asia. 4aarchival amnesia. 4aenchantment. 4ainter-religious relations. 4ajinn. 4apolitical theology. 4apost-colonial religion. 4aurban ecology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311070369640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360395040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503603950423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503603950.jpg  a978-3-11-070369-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles